<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 92 / Hyundai founder in new feud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ANOTHER political feud has broken out between the South Korean government
and Mr Chung Ju Yung, the founder of the Hyundai conglomerate, with
authorities alleging that a Hyundai subsidiary illegally funded Mr Chung's
Unification National party (UNP) in last month's National Assembly
elections.
The charges, which Hyundai denies, coincided with an announcement by Mr
Chung that he would probably run as the UNP's candidate in December's
presidential elections.
The Office of Bank Supervision (OBS) claims that Hyundai Electronic
Industries borrowed 4.8bn won (Pounds 3.6m) from the Korea Exchange Bank to
help finance the creation of the UNP in January.
Korean law stipulates that such loans should only be used for business
purposes.
Hyundai contends, however, that the money came from the proceeds of Hyundai
shares sold to the group's employees.
The UNP said the OBS allegations were part of a campaign by the authorities
to harm Mr Chung's reputation and divert attention from charges of
government vote-rigging in the recent parliamentary elections.
