<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 92 / Survey of Latin American Finance and Investment (12):
Nightmare begins to fade - Is the debt crisis over? / Examining the present
position
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE prospect that Brazil and Argentina will soon have outline debt
restructuring agreements with commercial banks has raised hopes that the
final chapter on the Latin American debt crisis will be concluded before its
10th anniversary. But are the hopes justified?
In the sense in which it was originally perceived - that of a threat to the
international banking system caused by the risk of widespread default by
Latin American governments on foreign bank debt - the crisis was over some
time ago.
However, the passing of the threat to the system did not mean an end of the
threat to individual banks. Some banks, particularly those in the US, took a
long time to recover. By the time the threat of their Third World debt had
receded, they had gathered a host of new problem loans closer to home.
Nonetheless, settlements with the first and third largest debtors in Latin
America should be an immense relief to many banks.
According to bank analysts at Salomon Brothers: 'If . . . Argentina and
Brazil each sign a Brady Plan-type agreement in 1992, the nightmare of the
cross-border overhang of the 1980s will fade rapidly into memory.'
From the point of view of the debtor countries, however, the picture is
different. Their emergence from the crisis has certainly been slower and
some economies remain overloaded by debt.
It is undeniable that their prospects improved significantly following the
launch three years ago of the debt initiative named after the US Treasury
Secretary, Mr Nicholas Brady. This shifted the emphasis of the international
debt strategy towards a reduction of bank debt burdens away from one which
inevitably encouraged further enlargement of debt stocks.
The psychological boost from the Brady debt agreement - coupled with tight
fiscal control and economic and trade reform - transformed international
perceptions of the Mexican economy. Moreover, the apparent economic success
of Mexico (and Chile, which eschewed a Brady-style debt restructuring) has
had a huge demonstration effect on economic policies in the rest of the
region.
Three questions arise:
To what extent do Brady-style debt restructuring agreements allow
governments to consign their debt problems to history?
To what extent are the capital inflows to Latin America building another
debt crisis for the future?
To what extent have the various debt initiatives provided the means for the
rest of the heavily indebted countries in the region to emerge from their
problems?
When viewed purely in cash-flow terms, the benefit of Mexico's Brady deal -
finally put into effect two years ago - was extremely modest. The recent
fall in US interest rates has, if anything, provided a greater reduction to
Mexico's debt servicing burden.
Most important was the confidence engendered by the accord. The announcement
of an agreement in principle with the banks in the summer of 1990 was enough
to trigger an immediate drop in domestic interest rates, which reduced the
government's cost of servicing its own short-term domestic debt. They have
continued to fall. Business confidence also boomed, helped by the
government's decision to negotiate a free trade accord with the US and
Canada.
In the cases of Argentina and Brazil, this confidence effect is going to be
smaller. Mr Lawrence Brainard, an economist with the US investment bank,
Goldman Sachs, in New York, reckons that in Argentina much of the effect of
an agreement with the commercial banks has been discounted. In the case of
Brazil, uncertainties over the government's fiscal position and its need
(because of a lack of resources) to spread out the provision of financial
guarantees to banks, suggests increased confidence will only accrue slowly.
Furthermore, the reduction in debt may be more modest even than in the
Mexican case. Brazil's Brady debt accord will cover only Dollars 40bn of
medium-term bank debt, compared to an end-1990 total foreign debt burden of
Dollars 116.2bn; Argentina's will cover Dollars 24bn of medium-term bank
debt, compared with a Dollars 61.1bn total. What is more, to make up for its
lack of resources to provide guarantees, Brazil will need to encourage a
larger proportion of banks to lend more money, rather than give debt relief.
Thus, while Brady deals will send important signals to the financial and
business communities inside and outside the two countries, they can provide
no guarantees that debt problems will not emerge again. Indeed, this cannot
be guaranteed - many would argue - without sustained economic reform to
correct imbalances in government budgets.
Nonetheless, the suggestion that the capital inflows into Latin America are
creating a new debt crisis is probably a little far-fetched, for now,
although it would probably be unwise to dismiss the possibility out of hand.
In the case of Mexico, which enjoys a huge share of the inflows, there are
reasons - in spite of a current account deficit likely to exceed Dollars
15bn this year - that differentiate what is happening today from what
happened in the late 1970s.
The government is running a budget surplus, even before privatisation,
receipts from which are being used to pay down government debt. The current
account deficit is thus a private sector phenomenon.
The government says a large proportion of the current account deficit arises
from imports of capital goods, rather than consumer items. Provided that
capital is used productively, such imports should provide returns to allow
repayment of any debt incurred for their purchase.
A significant proportion of the inflows are of equity rather than debt,
which cannot by definition cause a debt crisis.
Much of the new debt consists of fixed-rate bonds rather than floating rate
debt. It is thus less susceptible to an upward spike in US interest rates
than was the bank debt of the late 1970s. The international bond market
should also be more sensitive to credit and supply concerns than were
international banks in the 1970s, giving more scope for rationing by price.
Scenarios can be constructed whereby all this could degenerate into a new
problem: a financial crisis in the private sector, for example, that forces
the Mexican government to step in to take over private liabilities,
comparable to Chile's banking crisis of the 1980s. No such crisis is in
sight, however, and the probability of one emerging in the near future must
be rated as negligible.
For many of the region's smaller countries, however, the problems remain.
Many are hobbled by a large debt to foreign governments, or to the
international financial institutions such as the International Monetary
Fund.
For the poorest, such as Nicaragua, more generous concessions have been made
to reduce their debt servicing burdens, although the two-thirds debt
forgiveness envisaged in the UK's Trinidad Terms initiative has failed to
meet agreement among government creditors.
For slightly richer countries, particularly those who owe most of their debt
to governments rather than banks, the mechanisms exist only to chip away at
the debt burden.
The international financial institutions have been more flexible of late, as
have their leading shareholders, in helping countries dig themselves out of
arrears in payments to them. However, they have had to retain their
paramount concern for their own financial integrity. For those governments,
such as Peru, which owe a large part of their debt to such institutions, the
future still looks very difficult.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-14627</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDFBYAALFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920406
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 92 / Survey of Latin American Finance and Investment (13):
Interest in swaps flags / Debt Conversions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE push to convert sovereign debt into equity capital for local businesses,
once seen as one of the answers to the Latin American debt crisis, has
flagged of late.
Early attempts - such as Chile's move to convert some Dollars 10bn of
sovereign debt converted either into equity or other forms of debt - have
not been repeated. The main reason: the inflationary impact of such
programmes, which has acted as a disincentive across the region (though the
fact that the discount on Chilean debt has fallen to only around 10 per cent
of face value has also removed much of the attraction in its case).
Retiring debt at its face value forces governments to print money. The
antidote - issuing government debt to soak up the extra cash in the system -
can drive up local interest rates, and has come to be seen as
counter-productive.
As a result, debt-for-equity swaps are now seriously under consideration
only in relation to privatisation issues. Such schemes do not involve any
additional cash, and so have no inflationary repercussions. In principle,
the use of debt/equity swaps for privatisations has now been embraced by
Brazil, Argentina and Peru.
Of these, only Argentina has pushed ahead with the idea with vigour. Peru
has hinted that debt conversion will be possible in the planned
privatisation of around 25 local companies, though this remains a promise
rather than a reality. The country's foreign debt has not been snapped up in
anticipation, says Mr Ric Haller, head of LDC debt trading at Morgan
Grenfell in London. 'Peruvian debt is a speculative buy,' he says.
Brazil, on the other hand, has removed much of the attraction of converting
foreign debt into equity. Foreign debt faces a compulsory 25 per cent
discount - that is, it is bought back at 75 per cent of face value, rather
than the full amount. That has discouraged the use of such debt in
privatisations so far.
Efforts have been made in some quarters to have the discount restriction
relaxed. The National Development Bank, which is responsible for the
privatisation process in Brazil, has lobbied to have the rule changed,
arguing that this would attract more investors to privatisations and
maximise proceeds from sales.
That appeal was rejected last month, and observers do not expect a change of
heart in the foreseeable future. One concession was made, though: half of
Brazil's so-called 'PFA' debt, issued at the time of the 1988 parallel
financing agreement, is now available for use in debt/equity conversions,
making some Dollars 1.6bn available for this purpose, says Mr Igor
Cornelson, director of Standard Chartered Merchant Bank in San Paolo.
Domestic debt, which is accepted without a discount, has therefore become
the main vehicle for debt/equity swaps. There are attractions to Brazil in
maintaining this position: local debt generally carries a higher interest
rate and matures earlier than foreign debt, says Mr Cornelson. Local debt is
equally available to foreign companies with operations in the country -
though as yet, there are few signs of foreigners taking an interest in such
swaps.
Almost all the Dollars 1.7bn raised through privatisations in Brazil last
year consisted of local debt: 0.3 per cent was accounted for by foreign
debt, thanks to the fixed 25 per cent discount.
That leaves Argentina as the most active exponent of the debt/equity swap in
Latin America. Through a number of privatisations in the past 18 months,
significant amounts of foreign debt have been converted. Most notable have
been the privatisations of Aeorlineas Argentinas, control of which passed to
Iberia, the Spanish national carrier; and ENTel, the telephone company, 60
per cent of which was sold to two groups led by Citibank and J P Morgan.
Questions have been raised about whether it is desirable for the control of
important Argentine assets to pass into the hands of European state-owned
enterprises or international banks - particularly if the sales are at a
discount. But as a means of retiring debt, the privatisation process looks
set to continue.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-14628</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDFBYAAKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920406
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 92 / Survey of Latin American Finance and Investment (10):
Success follows a difficult birth - Brazil / Privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EDUARDO MODIANO, the head of Brazil's privatisation programme, has reason to
feel proud. Rarely has a programme had such an inauspicious beginning: the
auction of the Usiminas steel mill was mired in angry riots and legal
controversy. Six months and 30 legal processes later the programme is
running so smoothly that union leaders in three state steel companies have
asked for a speeding up so they can compete with the privatised companies.
Now on his eighth sale, Mr Modiano is focusing on increasing foreign
participation. So far this has been conspicuous by its absence, partly
frightened off by the Usiminas debacle and the instability of the Brazilian
economy, and partly deterred by the programme's rules. Of the Dollars 1.71bn
raised so far only 1.9 per cent has been in the form of foreign debt paper -
most of the rest coming from privatisation certificates (which financial
institutions were forced to buy in 1990-91) and domestic debt swapped at
face value.
Consequently, Mr Modiano has been stripping away restrictions to foreign
capital. A two-year lock-in period for shares in privatised companies has
been abolished allowing foreigners to trade or sell shares the next day.
Restrictions on remittances and dividends have been removed and the period
the capital must stay in Brazil has been reduced from 12 years to six.
The 40 per cent lid on voting capital remains but Mr Modiano points out that
the Congress is due to vote on a project ending regulatory discrim-ination
between foreign and Brazilian capital. 'Once that is accepted the 40 per
cent limit becomes redundant,' he says.
He is also lobbying hard to end the fixed 25 per cent discount on foreign
debt which he believes is the main deterrent to foreign participation,
holders of MYDFAs (the main foreign debt instrument) preferring to wait for
the hoped-for Brady type renegotiation of the commercial debt this year. Mr
Modiano is battling with the Central Bank to replace this discount with an
auction system. He argues: 'At the start of the programme we envisaged
Dollars 80bn available in privatisation currencies but this restriction has
kept out Dollars 45bn (the quantity of MYDFAs).'
Mr Modiano is eager for this to be revised before the petrochemical
companies go on sale because he believes there will be much foreign
interest.
Meanwhile, the two-sale-a-month schedule has been slowed down 'to meet with
the capacity of the market'. Though the first seven parastatals all fetched
more than the minimum price, since February one sale has been delayed and
two cancelled because of lack of buyers. Mr Modiano is resisting demands to
sell off the entire steel sector by the end of this year. 'We can't sell
five big steel companies each of around Dollars 1bn in five months. We have
to move with demand.' This year he will sell two steel mills - Acesita and
Tubarao.
The programme will not be completed during the present government's term.
Brazil has a huge state sector with more than 150 state-controlled companies
and several hundred more in which it has a minority interest. Mr Modiano
plans to sell at least 14 more companies to raise Dollars 3.4bn this year.
The programme now includes 32 companies and has been broadened to include
Embraer, the state aerospace company, and Lloyd Brasileiro, the state
shipping company, as well as RFFSA, the deeply indebted state railway.
But the sector which arouses most interest is telecommunications and many
foreign investors have eyes only for Telebras. A constitutional amendment to
end the state monopoly in infrastructure is due to go before Congress.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
