<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 92 / Survey of Latin American Finance and Investment (11): Star
performance after slow start - Venezuela / Privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOSEPH MANN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Venezuelan government's privatisation programme, announced with
considerable fanfare after the government of President Carlos Andres Perez
took office in early 1989, got off to a very slow start.
Late in 1990 the Venezuelan Investment Fund (Fondo de Inversiones de
Venezuela (FIV)), the government agency charged with carrying out
privatisation, sold the first state asset, a majority package of shares in a
commercial bank called Banco Occidental de Descuento.
But last year, Venezuela's privatisation programme put in a star
performance, obtaining Dollars 2.2bn in extra revenues for the government.
Through open bidding, the FIV sold off 60 per cent of shares in the
government's international airline, Viasa, to Iberia; sold two more
commercial banks (Italo Venezolano and Republica); a shipyard (Astinave); a
large sugar mill (El Tocuyo); a franchise to operate a cellular (mobile)
telephone system and the state-owned telecommunications company, CANTV.
By itself, CANTV would have made the privatisation programme a success. The
government received Dollars 1.89bn for 40 per cent of shares in the
telephone company, an equity package that allows the buyer to have full
operating control. The successful bid, made by an international consortium
headed by GTE (US), was Dollars 1bn above the government's minimum price.
Winning bidders must pay cash, and no debt-equity swaps are permitted.
This year, the FIV also has sold four hotels - the sales agreement was
signed a day after a military uprising was put down on February 4 - and
plans several other auctions.
Government assets to be sold this year include eight more hotels;
Aeropostal, an airline on domestic and international routes; six sugar
mills; the National Racetrack Institute (INH), which owns horse and
dog-racing tracks and other assets; the water company serving the Caracas
metropolitan area; and two or more regional electric power companies
(Enelven and Eneblar).
Other assets that may be sold are additional electric generating companies;
franchises to run toll highways; another shipyard (Dianca); a leading salt
producer (Ensal) and metal companies.
The government does not intend selling any parts of its profitable domestic
petroleum assets, but it wants to attract foreign investment for joint
ventures in exploration and production, refining and other sectors.
The government also has considerable holdings in petrochemicals, where it
works in a variety of joint ventures with Venezuelan and international
partners. There are no plans to sell any of these assets.
The government is also considering selling parts of the state-owned CVG
(Corporacion Venezolana de Guayana), which controls the country's heavy
industry. The announcement was made by Mr Jose Ignacio Moreno Leon, who as
minister of state and president of the Venezuelan Investment Fund, is the
head of Venezuela's privatisation programme. Although no firm decision has
been made, Mr Moreno said one candidate for privatisation would be Sidor,
the government-owned steel producer.
Sidor, which has had problems but recently made a profit, according to
government figures, is the largest steelmaker. Over the past few years,
Japanese investors considered starting a new steel complex in conjunction
with Sidor, but decided against it.
Aside from Sidor, the CVG group includes Venalum, the world's largest
aluminium smelter (a joint venture between the CVG and several Japanese
companies), other aluminium companies, iron ore and gold mining operations,
and Edelca, the largest hydroelectric company.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page V
</PAGE>
</DOC>
