<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 92 / Survey of Latin American Finance and Investment (6):
Investors react to free choice - Country Funds / Secondary Markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NOT SO long ago, international investors with a penchant for the emerging
markets of Latin America found that the simplest - and in some cases the
only - way to invest was through an appropriate country fund.
Today, they have more freedom of choice. The number of funds investing in
individual countries and in Latin America as a whole is increasing. However,
some large institutional investors are shifting away from collective
investments and turning to direct investment in the underlying equities
instead, as more and more Latin American countries ease restrictions on
direct investment and as the quality of research improves. In some markets,
such as Mexico, investors can easily invest in the main stocks so fund
managers say there is little point in using a country fund.
'There has been a change: the big investors are less preponderant (when it
comes to funds) because some are buying stocks and bonds on their own,' says
Mr Lincoln Rathnam, director of the Latin American group at fund managers
Scudder, Stevens &amp; Clark.
The ability to invest directly in certain Latin American markets may have
killed off demand for funds investing in those countries. For example, the
fund management group Genesis decided to wind up its Brazil unit trust once
it became easier to invest directly in equities there.
However, there are still plenty of investors who do want to use a selection
of diversified country funds to achieve a wider spread of investments. Mr
Rathnam claims that the percentage of retail investors in country funds has
increased as the markets become more accessible, and that some institutions
continue to use managed funds as 'they can find it difficult to follow the
markets'.
The fact remains for some countries - Chile is a prime example - the laws
governing investment by foreigners still mean it is easier to invest through
a managed fund.
Foreign investors who want to buy shares in Chilean companies have to set up
a special fund. The initial capital is tied up for a minimum of three years
and realised capital gains, interest and dividends are subject to a 10 per
cent withholding tax. Mr Anthony Newsome, managing director of Genesis, says
investors often see little point in setting up their own funds when they can
choose from existing quoted funds investing in Chile.
Mr Audley Twiston Davies, of Latin American Securities, whose Latin American
Investment Trust was the top performing investment trust in 1991, points out
that while countries such as Chile, Colombia, Venezuela and Peru charge tax
on investments, there is likely to be a trend towards lower taxes on
investment gains. Again, such a move might encourage international investors
to take the direct route rather than an open-ended or closed-end fund.
While the Latin American markets were among the top performers last year,
these markets remain very volatile and naturally this is reflected in the
performance of the country funds. 'You can get tremendous upswings and
downswings', points out Mr Rathnam. Indeed, Scudder's Brazil Fund showed a
68.3 per cent drop in capital in 1990 - which Mr Rathnam blames on the poor
performance of the stock market - before gaining 131.1 per cent in 1991. The
closed-end fund is now trading at a discount to net asset value of about 5
per cent.
Such volatility can pose more of a problem for open-ended than for
closed-end funds: if investors panic as the markets fall and want to redeem
their units quickly, the fund manager must be able to sell the underlying
investments easily. As a result, open-ended funds investing in this region
tend to concentrate on the larger, more liquid stocks while closed-end funds
have more freedom to buy small- and medium-sized companies for their
portfolio.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-14634</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDFBYAAEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920406
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 92 / Survey of Latin American Finance and Investment (4): New
magnet for funds - Stock Markets / Secondary Markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LATIN AMERICA has been an El Dorado for fortune-hunters through the
centuries but in recent years stock markets rather than promises of gold
have attracted overseas investors.
A return to democracy throughout the region after decades of rule by
military dictatorships and totalitarian regimes, and austere but necessary
economic restructuring have been the strongest magnets for foreign fund
managers. The rash of privatisations by most Latin American governments,
which have concentrated largely on the state telecommunications monopolies,
have added to the allure.
Believers in Latin America's ability to reform its economy and its political
system have, for the most part, been greatly rewarded. According to data
from the International Finance Corporation (IFC), part of the World Bank,
investors in Latin American equities enjoyed total returns in dollar terms
of 134 per cent in 1991. Argentina provided the biggest individual return,
up 396.6 per cent in dollar terms, while Venezuela brought up the rear with
a return of 48.4 per cent.
Fund managers interested in the region but unable, or unwilling, to invest
directly in the stock market of their preferred country, have either
entrusted their portfolios to specialist brokers or bought into one of
several regional or country funds. The sharp rises in the stock markets have
been reflected in the funds. For example, Latin American Investment Trust
was the best performer of all UK investment trusts last year, with its net
asset value rising by 124 per cent.
These results have not gone unnoticed by more conservative institutions, who
had decided not to invest in Latin America because of its history of
economic problems. The lack of market regulations and of critical research
by brokers keen on securing primary business, as well as difficulty in
understanding inflation accounting practices, have also been serious
barriers for the cautious foreign investor.
To a certain extent, these fears are being addressed. Mexico, which is the
region's largest and most liquid market, has virtually adopted US Gaap
(Generally Accepted Accounting Principles) and has also introduced strict
broker requirements. The Argentine government, which is planning further
privatisation issues this year, has given more powers to its National
Securities commission to crack down on stock market manipulation. In
February, two companies were suspended for alleged tax and trading offences.
The shift in international investors' attention away from the 'Tiger'
markets in the Pacific Basin towards Latin America has been reflected in the
number of securities houses now covering the region and this should lead to
more qualified company research. Furthermore, to attract the international
investors who dislike the lack of liquidity in the domestic markets, the
larger listed companies in Mexico, Argentina, Chile and Venezuela have
issued American Depository Receipts (ADRs) or shares and Global Deposit
Shares. Brazil's Telebras is also expected to offer ADRs soon.
But for all its progress, Latin America has retained its mercurial ability
to disappoint. A case in point is Venezuela, which in February suffered its
first military coup attempt since the early 1960s. The coup failed, but it
has forced President Carlos Andres Perez to back-pedal on his unpopular
economic reform and introduce constitutional changes. The stock market made
a satisfactory recovery immediately after the abortive uprising but it has
since fallen back. According to the IFC, Caracas fell by 14.8 per cent in
local currency terms in March, after a fall of 3 per cent in February, and
by 15 per cent in dollar terms because of continued weakness in the bolivar.
In the first three months, the market has dropped 3.8 per cent in local
currency terms and 5.4 per cent in dollar terms.
The recent developments in Venezuela have reminded equity investors of their
largest, single risk: that the region remains dependent on the continued
good health of a few individuals to safeguard reform and democracy.
Specialist brokers started to cover Peru after the appointment of President
Alberto Fujimori in 1990 signalled a radical change. A first generation
Peruvian and an academic, not from the traditional power bases, his
austerity programme has allowed the central bank to concentrate on long-term
monetary policies rather than the daily devaluation of the currency, so much
so that the new sol is appreciating against the dollar. This optimism has
also been reflected in the stock market, which rose 55.4 per cent in dollar
terms last year.
Over the next year, the biggest gains are expected to be in the smaller
markets which are judged to be undervalued. Mr Jeremy Campbell-Lamerton, a
director at Baring Securities, is optimistic about the prospects for Peru,
Chile and Colombia.
Brazil still has some scope to surprise, says Mr Audley Twiston Davies,
managing director of Latin American Securities, since its economy is twice
the size of Mexico's and it was one of the last in the region to be
restructured.
Most brokers believe Mexico is fast approaching its full value for now,
since the beneficial effects of the Free Trade Agreement with the United
States are largely being discounted by the stock market.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
