<DOCNO>FT922-14636</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDFBYAACFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920406
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 92 / Survey of Latin American Finance and Investment (3): Capital
flow expectations surpassed - The market for public bond issues may have
reached a watershed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE international market for public bond issues by Latin American borrowers,
which re-opened in 1989, has outstripped expectations in terms of volume and
performance.
Last year, capital flows to Latin America from bonds, private placements and
medium-term notes reached Dollars 8.5bn, according to research from Salomon
Brothers. Meanwhile, the yield differential between Eurodollar bonds for
Latin American issuers and US Treasuries has narrowed dramatically, as the
perception of Latin American credits improved.
But the market may now have reached a watershed. Deals for sovereign
borrowers such as Mexico and Venezuela, and for state-owned borrowers such
as Pemex (Petroleos Mexicanos), the state-owned oil company, which set the
market on its feet, have tightened substantially, and that trend may well
have run its course.
Five-year Mexican bonds are yielding 220 basis points more than the
comparable US Treasury, the same level as other improving sovereign credits
such as Turkey and Hungary. Such spreads mean that these bonds can no longer
be bracketed as high-yielding debt. US investors, for example, can buy the
lowest investment grade corporate bonds at spreads of around 150 basis
points.
The tightening of Mexican sovereign debt is 'close to over', according to Mr
Peter Bernard, managing director in charge of Latin American finance at J P
Morgan. 'I think Mexico will need a rating increase in order to tighten too
much further.'
Mexico is rated Ba2 by Moody's, and is widely expected to be in line for an
upgrade this year. Venezuela, currently rated Ba1, could also be due for an
upgrade, in spite of fears of political instability stirred up by the recent
failed coup.
The performance of Mexico and Venezuela, the first Latin American countries
to return to the market, was helped by their outstanding commercial debt
having been restructured through the Brady plan. Although Brazil and
Argentina, the two other countries to have gained access to the
international markets, have so far failed to reach an agreement on the
rescheduling of their debt, their public bond issues have also performed
well. In fact, when Brazil's secondary market debt prices slid on
disappointment that no rescheduling agreement had been reached last autumn,
Brazil's access to the international bond market was not affected.
Spreads of Brazilian bonds have also tightened. When Brazil returned to the
international capital markets last July, with a two-year issue for Petrobras
(Petroleo Brasileiro), the state-owned oil company, the deal was priced to
yield 650 basis points above the comparable Treasury. The launch spread for
two-year public sector bonds is now between 350 basis points and 400 basis
points, and banks are trying to push spreads even tighter.
As in other sectors, borrowers, at first able to raise only one- or two-year
funds, can now borrow over increasingly long maturities. Telebras
(Telecomunicacoes Brasileiras), the telecommunications group, last month
launched a Dollars 90m deal maturing in 1997, with a put option after three
years priced to yield 450 basis points over the three-year Treasury yield.
Although there could be room for some further improvement in Brazilian bond
spreads, likely to be triggered by a debt rescheduling agreement which is
again believed to be close, the dramatic spread tightening of the last nine
months is not likely to be repeated, according to traders.
The next stage of the market's development will be to grant access to a
broader range of private sector companies. Already, an increasing number of
Mexican and Brazilian companies are looking at it.
'Once Latin American sovereign borrowers are no longer breaking the ground,
there will be more visible differentiation between corporate credits,
especially in the private sector,' said Mr Jorge Jasson, managing director
in charge of emerging markets at Chase Manhattan. 'The market will require
more careful credit analysis.'
The market, so far limited to Mexico, Venezuela, Brazil and Argentina, is
also likely to open to other countries.
Uruguay is expected to return to the capital markets shortly with a Dollars
75m deal via J P Morgan. However, the deal is not likely to pave the way for
corporate issues from Uruguay, due to the small size of the country's
economy
Some bankers say Chile is also likely to tap the international capital
markets, and would be well received. Although Chile does not need to borrow,
and there is an active domestic market for Chilean companies, some borrowers
may wish to diversify their sources of funds.
The tightening of spreads of Latin American Eurobonds has not simply been
the result of improving credit. The market has managed to attract an
increasingly broad range of investors. 'The Eurobond investor base
originally consisted of mainly offshore flight capital held in centres like
Luxembourg and Switzerland,' said Mr Miles Protter, director of emerging
markets at Swiss Bank Corporation. 'But we have had considerable success in
bringing institutional investors and fund managers into the market.'
Recently, large companies with spare liquidity have also invested in the
market, he added.
Most Latin American Eurobonds have incorporated a '144a option', which
allows the bonds to be placed with US institutional investors through the
private placement market, under the Securities and Exchange Commission's
rule 144a. The response from US investors has ranged 'from good to
disappointing', according to Mr Protter. While around 15 per cent of some
deals was placed in the US, in other cases, US institutional investors have
found yields too aggressive, compared with paper available in the US high
yield corporate, or junk, bond market.
To achieve a more diverse investor base, Mexico, in particular, has led the
way in tapping other sectors of the market, as well as extending maturity.
Banamex (Banco Nacional de Mexico) launched a Pta10bn five-year deal in the
Spanish 'matador' bond market earlier this year, while Nafinsa (Nacional
Financiera) raised Ecu100m of five-year bonds in February.
The trend towards increasing diversity - of credit, of country, of currency
and of maturity - is likely to fuel continued interest in the sector over
the next few years.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page II
</PAGE>
