<DATE>920404
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 APR 92 / SIB defends soft-commission share trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CALLS FOR a ban on so-called 'soft commission' share trading were turned
down yesterday by the Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief
investment regulator, which issued its strongest statement in defence of the
practice.
Under soft commission arrangements, institutional investors promise to give
business to a particular broker. In return, the institutions receive
facilities that help them do their job, such as information services or
screens carrying market news and data. Critics say the arrangements prevent
investors from shopping round to get the best deal for clients each time
they trade.
The practice was criticised recently by Mr Peter Rawlins, chief executive of
the London Stock Exchange. He called on pension fund investment managers to
drop soft commissions. 'To the average man, if people want a service, they
should be prepared to pay visibly for it in a currency everyone
understands,' he added.
Yesterday, the SIB said it had noted calls to review its policy on soft
commissions or to ban the practice, but it had decided no change was
necessary.
'Soft commission arrangements provide a legitimate means for fund managers
to obtain specialist services,' the board said. 'The payment of commission
in return for an array of services in addition to execution, which benefit
the fund manager's clients, is a traditional feature of the marketplace.'
The board said that to prevent abuse it had developed a framework to define
the services that could be provided, to keep customers informed and to
ensure that 'transactions are carried out on terms no different from those
involving a traditional commission arrangement'.
Those regulatory arrangements should be given a chance to settle down, it
said, adding that trustees 'should be alert to the implications for fund
beneficiaries of such arrangements'.
The board also said it would take no action to limit the ability of
integrated investment houses to undertake soft commission business. It had
started a review of the subject, prompted by moves by some integrated houses
to cut soft commission rates to win business.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 24
</PAGE>
