FT  04 APR 92 / International Company News: Paul Reichmann quits CIBC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Paul Reichmann, co-owner and chief strategist of Olympia &amp; York, the
financially-strapped property developer, has quietly resigned from the board
of Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce, the company's main banker and largest
creditor.
An official spokesman for CIBC, Canada's second biggest financial
institution, had no comment yesterday on Mr Reichmann's position. But
another source said Mr Reichmann submitted his resignation several months
ago, before a liquidity crisis forced O&amp;Y to ask its creditors to
restructure its USDollars 20bn debt.
Canadian banks traditionally invite representatives of their most valued
customers to sit on their boards. CIBC has refused to comment in any way on
its relationship with O&amp;Y. But Canadian banking analysts have estimated
CIBC's exposure at about CDollars 1bn.
CIBC, meanwhile, has named Mr Al Flood as its next chairman and chief
executive.
Mr Flood, aged 56 and head of CIBC's corporate banking unit, will succeed Mr
Donald Fullerton who is retiring after seven years in the top job. The
appointment takes effect on June 7.
Mr Flood has had responsibility for the bank's negotiations with O&amp;Y. He is
unlikely to make any large changes in the short-term, beyond overseeing an
expansion into insurance and fiduciary services when regulatory barriers are
lifted on June 1.
