FT  04 APR 92 / Labour tax plans may deter expatriates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR'S TAX proposals would make London a less attractive location for
expatriates than other European cities, according to an analysis by a
consultancy group, Andrew Jack writes.
The International Employer, part of Sedgwick Financial Services, said
yesterday London would become the most costly of a selection of European
cities after Brussels for an expatriate upper middle manager with two
children on a three-year contract at Dollars 1.38m (Pounds 790,000).
London is currently the fourth most costly, at Dollars 1.04m, after
Brussels, Paris and Geneva, assuming a basic annual salary of Dollars 84,000
plus school fees and housing allowances.
The analysis does not include the effect of tax changes that might take
place in any other countries.
