</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FIERCE fighting erupted in Croatia yesterday, a day before United Nations
peace-keeping troops were due to start arriving to police a truce in the
former Yugoslav republic, Reuter reports from Belgrade.
Hospital officials in the north-eastern Croatian town of Osijek said 12
people were killed and 28 injured in an attack in which the hospital itself
was also hit.
Police in the town of Valpovo, 30km to the west, said five people were
killed and 10 injured in an attack there. Belgrade television reported two
deaths just across the border in the republic of Bosnia-Hercegovina.
The fighting, among the most serious in Croatia this year, erupted one day
before the first part of a 14,000-strong UN force was due to arrive to try
to stop nine months of conflict over Croatia's secession from Yugoslavia.
Violence also flared in Bosnia, prompting its leaders to ask the UN for help
to end fighting which has killed more than 30 people in the past week and
increased fears of civil war among its mixed population of Moslems, Croats
and Serbs.
Belgrade television said two people were killed in the Bosnian town of
Bosanski Brod.
