<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow declines as jobs data is
awaited
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
TRADING on US stock markets remained subdued yesterday ahead of a key
employment report, and share prices finished lower across the board
following another big fall in Japanese equities overnight, writes Patrick
Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average ended 15.21 down at 3,234.12, while the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 declined 3.73 to 400.50. The Nasdaq composite index of
over-the-counter stocks fell 8.27 to 593.82. Turnover on the New York SE
totalled a modest 185m shares.
US markets are concerned about the sharp falls on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
because they fear this will force Japanese investors to repatriate funds,
which could mean withdrawing money from US stock and bond markets.
Domestic economic factors also weighed heavily on investors. Today's March
jobs data should help clear some of the uncertainty surrounding the US
economy, and analysts are forecasting a rise in those in work, which would
confirm the recent trend of a gradual improvement in labour conditions.
The big three motor stocks were in mixed form, in spite of hopes among some
investors that car sales will rebound in line with the economic recovery.
Ford put on Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 39 1/2 . Chrysler lost Dollars  3/8 to
Dollars 17 1/2 and General Motors Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 36 1/2 .
CMS Energy plunged Dollars 6 to Dollars 15 3/4 in turnover of 3.3m shares
after the Michigan Public Service Commission turned down a proposal by the
company to settle various rate issues that are pending.
CUC International rose Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 33 3/8 after broking house
Alex Brown raised its rating on the electronic shopping service group from
'hold' to 'buy'.
On the over-the-counter market, Immunex plummeted Dollars 10 1/2 to Dollars
31 1/2 after the company said it expected to post a first-quarter loss. The
market had been expecting profits of about 9 cents a share in the quarter.
Goal Systems jumped Dollars 3 1/2 to Dollars 18 3/4 in heavy trading after
it was announced that the developer of IBM-compatible software will be
bought by another software group, Legent, for Dollars 400m in stock. Under
the deal, each share of Goal will be swapped for just over half a Legent
share. Legent dropped Dollars 4 1/4 to Dollars 36 1/2 .
Canada
TORONTO followed Wall Street's downtrend during fairly heavy trading, the
composite index finishing 16.0 lower at 3,395.9. Falls outnumbered advances
by 320 to 231 after volume of 33.2m shares.
Corel Systems, off CDollars 1 7/8 at CDollars 17 1/8 , reported
first-quarter earnings from continuing operations of CDollars 1.97m or 17
cents a share, down from CDollars 2.8m or 26 cents a year ago.
