FT  03 APR 92 / International Company News: General Motors puts gas turbine
unit up for sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GENERAL MOTORS, the US automotive manufacturer in the throes of a large
restructuring, yesterday announced that it was looking for a buyer for its
Allison Gas Turbine Division.
Allison, which employs some 6,300 people, designs and makes turbine engines
for the aerospace, industrial and marine industries. GM bought the business
in 1929. It has manufacturing and research facilities in Indianapolis,
Indiana.
Mr William Hoglund, GM's executive vice-president in charge of Allison, said
the sale was consistent with the company's strategy of focusing its energy
on improving the competitive position of its core businesses.
Last December GM announced plans for more than 70,000 jobs losses and the
closure of 21 plants over the next few years to return its heavily
loss-making US automotive operations to profit.
In recent years the group has spun off several large peripheral activities,
notably Detroit Diesel, which under new management turned from a loss-maker
into a profitable, entrepreneurial business.
Mr Blake Wallace, general manager of Allison, yesterday sought to reassure
customers - many of them foreign governments - that it would keep its
operations stable during the transition from GM ownership.
