FT  03 APR 92 / International Company News: O&amp;Y to seek suspension of debt
repayments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON and BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OLYMPIA &amp; YORK is expected to ask its banks for a formal suspension of
repayments on its debt, which exceeds Dollars 20bn, to provide time for an
agreement to be reached on a permanent reorganisation of borrowings.
However, O&amp;Y has been forced to postpone a meeting of all its banks which
had been scheduled for Monday.
The task of condensing information on all its borrowings, provided by more
than 100 banks, proved too great in the time. O&amp;Y said yesterday that it now
plans to hold the meeting on April 13. The company said in a statement that
it will put forward an interim proposal at the meeting while it negotiates a
longer-term plan. In addition, it plans to provide detailed information
about what it described as its 'legal and organisation structures', and its
financial condition.
Last week, O&amp;Y was given an informal promise by 20 banks with the biggest
loans to it that they would suspend debt repayments in advance of a meeting
of all the banks.
A complete reorganisation of O&amp;Y's debt is expected to take two years. O&amp;Y
hopes its banks will suspend principal repayments until the reorganisation
is completed. A steering committee of O&amp;Y's banks is being led by Citicorp,
Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce and the Hongkong and Shanghai Banking
Corporation.
One item on the agenda at the full bank meeting is likely to be a request
for funds to allow work to continue at the Canary Wharf development in
London's Docklands.
