<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 92 / Indemnity notice from Lime Street nearly month late
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LIME STREET Underwriting Agency, the Lloyd's members' agency that went into
liquidation in early March, told its Names it had not renewed its indemnity
insurance nearly one month after the policy had expired, in spite of an
instruction from Lloyd's to do so at once, it emerged yesterday.
Notification came in late July last year, although the policy had lapsed in
June. By then, legal claims for liability by Names against the agency may
have been hindered.
Names managed by Lime Street make up a high proportion of the membership of
large loss-making syndicates such as Gooda Walker 387, which has an
estimated loss of 750 per cent of pledged assets for 1988. Names are
individuals whose assets underwrite insurance at Lloyd's.
A letter sent by Mr David Coleridge, chairman of Lloyd's, to underwriting
agencies on April 11 last year and obtained by the Financial Times says
members' agents should notify their Names 'immediately' if they were not
renewing their errors and omissions (E&amp;O) cover, or doing so on a more
restricted basis.
Lime Street did not send out letters to its Names informing them that it was
not renewing E&amp;O cover until July 22 1991, at which point it told them the
policy had expired on June 30.
A number of Names had already notified Lime Street of potential claims on
the advice of action groups formed by members of some of the worst suffering
syndicates.
Until last year, when Lloyd's relaxed the regulations, E&amp;O insurance was
compulsory for both members' and underwriting agencies.
Directors of Lime Street told creditors at a meeting when the company was
liquidated last month that the delay in notifying them was caused by
continued attempts to obtain cover at affordable premiums, which proved
impossible.
Representatives of Lime Street refuse to give any details of the E&amp;O policy,
arguing that any information might jeopardise payments by the underwriters.
Lime Street's E&amp;O policy is believed to have been written on a 'claims made'
basis, however, which means it will cover only claims notified before the
expiry of the policy.
The notifications from Names by that time are likely to have formed an
important part of the estimate of claims given by Lime Street to its
underwriters.
The statement of affairs presented to creditors at a meeting last month
showed claims totalling about Pounds 21m against the company so far. A
number of others were unquantified because they are dependent on losses that
are not yet known.
It also emerged yesterday that one of the Lime Street directors in the mid
1970s was Mr Frederick Sasse, a Lloyd's underwriter whose syndicate ran up
heavy losses arising from its insurance of properties in US cities.
Mr Sasse was a director of Lime Street Underwriting between 1976 and 1978.
He had been a director of Saturn Insurance, which became Lime Street in
1976, when Mr Robin Kingsley joined the board.
</TEXT>
