<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 92 / Bonuses paid early to avoid Labour tax plans: City's poll
fears seen as cause of payments shift
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE has been a marked increase in the number of companies bringing forward
bonus payments to avoid the possibility of being affected by Labour's
proposed tax increases.
Computer Management Group, which claims to process 10 per cent of the UK's
payroll market, says it has noted a distinct shift in bonus payments across
a broad sector of industry.
Mr John Benson, the group's managing director, said: 'While it is not
uncommon for companies to make bonus payments at this point in the financial
year, the only obvious conclusion that can be drawn from our observations is
that companies are making these payments in the 1991-92 tax year rather than
take the risk of potentially higher rates in the 1992-93 tax year.'
He added that the company's confidentiality clause prohibited him from
naming any of the companies involved.
A number of banks and stockbrokers in the City, which normally award bonuses
in the late spring and early summer, have brought them forward. Smith New
Court, for example, said it had brought forward a proportion of each
person's bonus to avoid the possibility of higher tax under Labour.
The apparent acceptance that Labour might win the election is an
embarrassment to some City firms. As recently as early March, 48 per cent of
Smith New Court's fund manager clients thought the election would lead to an
overall majority for the Tories.
Other city firms that are believed to have brought forward bonuses include
SG Warburg and Robert Fleming.
Indications that bonus payments have increased in the approach to the
general election follow reports from accountants that clients have been
seeking other 'tax-efficient' measures so that they will receive income in
the current financial year.
</TEXT>
