<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 92 / The high cost of bouncing cheques
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE number of bouncing cheques has risen sharply and high-fashion stores are
particularly vulnerable, according to a company that guarantees cheques for
about 37,000 retailers.
The risk of default is nearly twice as high with business cheques as with
personal cheques, Birmingham-based Transax says.
Transax reported yesterday that for every 10,000 cheques covering sums above
the normal bank card guarantee limit of Pounds 50 which passed through the
retail and banking system last year, 67 personal cheques and 114 business
cheques bounced.
Compared with 1990, defaults last year rose 17 per cent for personal cheques
and 9.5 per cent for business cheques. The disparity arises because business
cheque defaults were much higher in 1990 than personal cheque defaults, so
the risk in handling personal cheques rose more quickly last year than that
for business cheques.
Retailers using the Transax service telephone for authority to accept
cheques covering amounts above the bank guarantee limit. Transax then checks
the details against its own database - it has no access to bank files. Once
it gives an authorisation, Transax is bound to see that the retailer is paid
in full and it takes responsibility for recovering the sum written on a
bounced cheque. The average value of its guarantee is Pounds 120 for
personal cheques and Pounds 160 for business cheques.
Of more than 5m cheques covered by a Transax guarantee last year, twice as
many bouncing personal cheques were presented in menswear shops as in cycle
shops. In the business sector, the number of bouncing cheques taken by the
motor and building trades rose by 19 per cent and 23 per cent respectively.
Bouncing cheques are more likely to come from those with personal accounts
at building societies than at clearing banks, the analysis showed.
</TEXT>
