<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 92 / Election 1992: Mellor condemns sell-off 'muddle'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR was accused yesterday by Mr David Mellor, chief secretary to the
Treasury, of 'muddle and confusion' over privatisation.
His attack came after Mr John Smith, the shadow chancellor, said that his
party had made 'no decisions' on whether a Labour government would sell the
residual shareholdings in British Telecom and the two electricity generation
companies.
Earlier, Mr Neil Kinnock had said that his party would not stop any of the
sales that were already in the pipeline. That would mean that the same
resources would be available to Labour as the Conservatives next year. But
Mr Mellor called on Mr Kinnock to clarify whether a Labour government would
announce new privatisation schemes on top of those already planned.
His intervention followed a series of Conservative attempts this week - so
far resisted by Labour - to force Mr Kinnock to clarify its projections for
public-sector borrowing over the medium-term.
Mr Mellor suggested that if Labour took power and failed to go ahead with
new privatisation programmes, the public-sector accounts would be a further
Pounds 9bn in deficit over the two financial years starting in April 1993.
Mr Mellor said the Tories planned to gain Pounds 8bn from privatisation in
this financial year, followed by Pounds 5.5bn in both 1993-4 and 1994-5.
If Labour took power, it would obtain the Pounds 8bn due this financial year
from programmes already started, but would gain at most Pounds 2bn for the
subsequent two years, unless it announced new schemes. Mr Mellor said the
Conservatives could achieve their own target for privatisation and called on
Labour to be more specific on its plans.
</TEXT>
