FT  03 APR 92 / Election 1992: Teachers' vote - Ballot Box
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Should John Major fall under a bus next Thursday, it is said that Kenneth
Clarke would not mind applying for the vacancy.
This week's ICM poll of teachers - his flock as education secretary - won't
exactly boost his chances.
The poll showed that after 18 months of bullying from Clarke, Tory support
among Britain's 450,000 teachers has plummeted to 20 per cent - against 51
per cent for Labour.
In the halcyon days of 1979, polls showed that 45 per cent of the nation's
teachers were behind the Thatcher banner.
'They're voting for a quiet life,' was the characteristically robust
response from the education secretary.
