<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 92 / Election 1992: Nuclear stand was 'error of judgment'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NEIL KINNOCK last night candidly admitted to errors of judgment in his
support for unilateral nuclear disarmament and failure to campaign to change
Labour's policy on the European Community after the 1975 referendum.
His admission, in an ITV interview with Sir Robin Day, came after the Labour
leader denied that his readiness for an all-party commission on electoral
reform was an 'open door' to a pact with the Liberal Democrats.
Looking confident and relaxed, Mr Kinnock said he had believed unilateral
disarmament was the only means of breaking the 'log jam' in the build-up of
nuclear weapons. On reflection this 'may have been an error of judgment'.
On the EC, Mr Kinnock said that in retrospect he believed Labour should have
accepted the verdict of the 1975 plebiscite which overwhelmingly supported
continued British EC membership. But he added that he was guided by the
principle of collective responsibility which precluded him from publicly
opposing the party.
In the event he changed his own position shortly before the 1983 election
and made his views known afterwards. 'Such was the turmoil and the weakness
in my party, to which I owe a duty, I wasn't going to inflict an additional
burden,' he said.
Questioned on devolution, Mr Kinnock denied that he had opposed the move on
principle, but only in the form proposed by the Callaghan government's
referendum in 1978.
He also strongly defended Labour's tax and national insurance plans, set to
raise total deductions for top payers to 59 per cent.
</TEXT>
