<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 92 / US clears Israel of selling Patriot secrets to China
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE and HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US yesterday issued Israel 'a clean bill of health' on charges that it
had transferred Patriot missile technology to China.
But Ms Margaret Tutwiler, the state department spokesman, refused to address
allegations in a department report on Wednesday that an unnamed country -
widely assumed to be Israel - had engaged in 'a systematic and growing
pattern' of unauthorisied sales of sensitive US military technologies to
third countries.
The two sets of charges must be treated separately, Ms Tutwiler said.
The allegations have worsened relations between the US and Israel, already
at odds over the US refusal to provide loan guarantees unless the Israelis
stop building new settlements in occupied Arab territories.
The alleged transfer of Patriot technology came to light in a leaked
intelligence report. Mr Dick Cheney, defence secretary, said he had 'good
reason' to be-lieve the report.
But Ms Tutwiler said a 17-member team sent to Israel to investigate the
matter had 'found no evidence that Israel had transferred a Patriot missile
or Patriot missile technology.'
The separate charges of numerous violations of US export controls were
contained in a report issued on Wednesday by the State Department's
inspector general, Mr Sherman Funk. He contended that there had been 'a
systematic and growing pattern' of unauthorised sales of a major recipient
of US military assistance.
He did not refer specifically to Israel, but administration officials
acknowledged privately that it was Israel. It was suggested that the two
major recipients of the arms were South Africa and China.
The investigation of the Patriot transfer was 'a stand-alone, separate
mission' which must not be confused with the inspector general's report, Ms
Tutwiler said.
The Bush administration has been admonished by Mr Bill Clinton - the leading
contender for the Democratic party's presidential nomination - for
'browbeating' Israel over its settlements policy. As a result, the arms
transfer controversy has been handled very gingerly.
In Jerusalem earlier, Israel repeated its denial that it had sold US arms
and technology to countries such as China and South Africa in the face of US
and international prohibitions.
Israeli officials continued to demand a public retraction of allegations by
the US. 'Our policy is to adhere strictly to the procurements and technology
transfer agreements,' said Mr Danny Naveh, spokesman for Mr Moshe Arens, the
defence minister.
The Israeli government is bracing itself for much tougher scrutiny of US
arms and technology transfers, on which the Israeli defence forces and
military industries have come to depend. The military is worried it may
become subject to sanctions on some technologies to which it wants access to
maintain Israel's 'qualitative edge' over its Arab foes.
Despite the official denials, the US moves have forced Israel to be somewhat
more open about its secretive military exports.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
